{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01XPzz5ziT3XxdcSKL3PpLMq","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"This is a test plan creation task for an email drafting assistant system. I need to analyze 5 behaviors and determine the minimum test level needed to catch real failures for each.\n\nLet me understand the context:\n- System: autonomous email drafting assistant\n- Main flow: read email thread → generate reply via LLM → check facts vs KB → present to user → user approves → send\n- Behaviors to test:\n\n1. Generated reply references specific points from incoming email (not generic)\n2. Factual consistency check flags contradictions with knowledge base\n3. When KB has no entries, draft includes disclaimer (not fabricated)\n4. Approval workflow blocks sending until explicit approval\n5. Full end-to-end sequence works\n\nLet me analyze each using the framework:\n\n## Behavior 1: Generated reply references specific points from incoming email\n\n**Description**: The generated reply references specific points from the incoming email rather than producing a generic response.\n\n**What would fail?**\n- The reply generator ignores the email context and produces boilerplate\n- Threading context is lost\n- Email parsing fails silently\n\n**Mock-miss analysis**: \n- If I mock the LLM to return a fixed string, I can test that the context is being *passed* to the LLM\n- But I can't verify that a real LLM actually uses those specific points when generating\n- The real failure is: \"given the same context, a real LLM sometimes ignores the specifics and produces generic text\"\n- OR: \"the email parsing/context extraction fails in subtle ways that a real LLM can't work around\"\n\n**LLM-dependency?**\n- YES - whether the reply references specific points depends on what the real LLM generates\n- Different LLM versions, temperatures, prompts may vary\n- The test must use a real LLM or at least verify the context reaches it and is non-generic\n\n**Minimum level**: This is tricky. Let me think about what would catch a real failure:\n\n\n- Unit tests can isolate email parsing and prompt construction separately, catching failures where context is stripped or malformed before reaching the LLM\n- Integration tests can verify the full pipeline with a real LLM call, catching cases where the model ignores context despite receiving it correctly\n- The test should provide a multi-point email and verify the draft references at least N specific details, which requires either a real LLM call (Agentic level) or a deterministic mock that validates the context payload is complete and non-generic\n\nThe core issue is whether the real LLM actually produces output grounded in specifics. Mocking always passes, so I need an Agentic test that calls a real LLM to catch the failure where context is received but ignored. Unit and Integration tests can validate the pipeline up to the LLM, but only a real call verifies the output quality.\n\nFor the factual consistency check, I'm looking at what could break: the checker might miss contradictions, KB lookups could fail silently, or claims could bypass verification entirely. The test needs to catch these real failures.\n\nThe key question is whether the consistency check uses an LLM to evaluate contradictions or relies on rule-based matching. If it's LLM-based, then real LLM behavior determines whether subtle contradictions get caught or false positives occur. If it's rule-based, an Integration test with a real KB would suffice. Given the complexity of evaluating \"factual consistency,\" it likely uses an LLM, which means the minimum level is Agentic—I need real LLM judgment to verify the checker actually identifies contradictions correctly. LM evaluation? The KB lookup is an Integration or System concern depending on storage, while contradiction detection is Agentic if LLM-based or Unit if rule-based. The core behavior—flagging contradictions—fails if the checker doesn't actually catch them. For an LLM-based checker, I need Agentic testing to confirm the real model detects contradictions; for deterministic logic, Integration suffices to verify KB integration works. Most likely, the email system extracts claims, queries the KB, then uses an LLM to evaluate contradictions—requiring Agentic coverage for the full behavior. A Unit test that just verifies the checker runs and returns something wouldn't catch the real failure of missing actual contradictions.\n\nThe minimum level depends on implementation. If rule-based, Integration catches KB failures and logic gaps. If LLM-based, only Agentic testing verifies the model actually flags contradictions. Given the robustness concern, I'd lean toward Agentic as the safest answer, though Integration is the prerequisite baseline.\n\nFor the contradiction detection itself, the challenge is that \"factual consistency\" involves nuanced matching—same facts stated differently, contextual contradictions. This likely requires real LLM evaluation rather than mocks. Integration tests KB connectivity, but Agentic testing ensures the checker genuinely catches subtle mismatches.\n\nMoving to the next behavior: when the knowledge base lacks relevant entries, the draft should include a disclaimer instead of inventing facts. The real failure mode here is the model generating unsupported claims when KB coverage is incomplete.\n\nMocking an empty KB only verifies that a disclaimer appears in that scenario, but doesn't test whether the actual LLM resists fabrication. The core risk—LLM hallucination when sources are unavailable—requires running against a real model. Integration confirms KB plumbing works; Agentic confirms the model behaves responsibly under knowledge scarcity. This also demands real LLM execution to validate the behavior.\n\n---\n\nFor the approval workflow, the key question is whether sending gets blocked until explicit user sign-off. The failure modes are straightforward: draft goes out without approval, the system skips the approval check, or the UI gets circumvented. Since this is pure control flow—generate draft, require approval, gate the send action—I can verify it through logic testing without mocking. The approval check itself has no LLM dependency. Whether I need Integration or Unit depends on whether the send action touches a real email API or just a database flag; if it's just checking an approval flag in memory or a local store, Unit suffices.\n\nFor the end-to-end sequence with a real email thread, the concern shifts to whether all the integration points work together—reading the thread, generating the draft, fact-checking, and presenting for approval all functioning as one flow.\n\nThe real failure modes emerge at the boundaries: output formats don't align between steps, threading logic breaks across components, email parsing fails on real messages, or async coordination stumbles. If I mock everything, the test passes regardless of whether the actual pieces fit together. The test needs real email parsing, actual LLM calls for draft generation and fact-checking, and real KB lookups to catch integration failures that mocks would hide.\n\nThis is heavily LLM-dependent with multiple agentic steps chained together, and involves real I/O across email reading, LLM calls, and potentially the approval interface. Minimum: Integration\n- Unit: 0.1 (could stub KB responses)\n- Integration: 0.7 (KB availability is the key dependency)\n- System: 0.1 (external KB adds complexity)\n- Agentic: 0.05 (LLM not central here)\n- Workflow: 0.05 (single conditional step)\n\nSum: 1.0 ✓\n\n## Behavior 4: Approval workflow\n\nMinimum: Workflow\n- Unit: 0.05 (can't test real approval without orchestration)\n- Integration: 0.1 (approval + email together, but no multi-step sequencing)\n- System: 0.05 (email is real, but approval logic is simple)\n- Agentic: 0.1 (single decision point)\n- Workflow: 0.65 (requires coordinating generate → check → approve → send steps)\n\nSum: 1.0 ✓\n\n## Behavior 5: Full end-to-end sequence\n\nMultiple agentic steps with real dependencies—LLM generates draft, checks facts against KB, flags contradictions, waits for approval, then sends. This is the core workflow test.\n\nFor behavior 2, I need to determine whether the contradiction detection uses an LLM or rule-based matching. If the system uses an LLM to evaluate semantic consistency between draft claims and KB entries, that pushes the minimum toward Agentic. If it's pattern-matching on explicit contradictions, Integration suffices. I'll assume LLM-based reasoning given the sophistication implied.\n\nBehavior 1 also needs clarification—testing whether the reply actually engages with specific email content rather than generating boilerplate requires verifying the LLM output references particular points from the incoming message.\n\nTo validate this at Integration level, I could mock the LLM to return a predetermined response containing those references and verify the input includes the specific points. However, the real test is whether an actual LLM produces contextual references when given the email. A mock always passes; a real model might default to generic text. This suggests Agentic minimum is necessary. Using a real LLM with fixed parameters could work at Integration, but randomness introduces flakiness, which the guidance discourages.\n\nThe core issue: LLM outputs vary across runs due to temperature, model versions, and inherent non-determinism. Since outcomes differ with the same input, this falls into Agentic territory. For the other behaviors, I'm categorizing references as Agentic, contradiction detection as Integration (or Agentic if LLM-dependent), empty KB disclaimers as Agentic, approval logic as Unit, and the full workflow as Workflow-level.\n\nFor the contradiction-flagging behavior specifically, the key question is whether the detection mechanism is deterministic. A rule-based approach would suffice at Integration level—mock the KB with known contradictory entries and verify the flag triggers. But if the checker uses an LLM to identify contradictions, non-determinism creeps in and pushes toward Agentic testing.\n\nAssuming a simpler rule-based implementation, Integration becomes the minimum viable level. The allocation would weight Integration heavily at 0.6, with smaller portions for Unit testing claim extraction (0.1), System testing if the KB is external (0.1), and Agentic coverage only if LLM evaluation is involved (0.15), leaving minimal Workflow weight at 0.05.\n\nRather than continuing to layer complexity, I should apply the framework more directly to the behavior itself. The core question is whether a mocked knowledge base would suffice to validate the flagging mechanism, or if real-world variability demands something closer to Agentic-level testing.\n\nMocking both the KB and the checker creates a false pass—the behavior appears to work when both components are stubbed. Catching the actual failure requires either a genuine KB paired with a rule-based checker, or a real KB with an LLM-based evaluator. Integration testing with a real knowledge base and rule-based logic forms the baseline, though LLM-based contradiction detection pushes toward Agentic. I'll weight Integration at 0.55 as the primary level, assign 0.30 to Agentic for LLM scenarios, and distribute the remainder across Unit (0.05), System (0.05), and Workflow (0.05).\n\nMoving to behavior 4 now—the approval workflow that prevents automatic sending without explicit user consent. The critical failure mode is a draft being transmitted despite the approval gate. Testing requires attempting to send and confirming the block engages.\n\nA unit-level test can verify the control flow by mocking the email mechanism and asserting the approval check executes. However, if approval state lives in persistent storage and someone retrieves a draft from the database without re-validating approval status, that gap only surfaces through integration or system testing. The simplest failure—missing the approval check entirely—is catchable at unit level, but bypassing the check through workflow state manipulation demands integration coverage. I'll set Unit at 0.65 as the minimum, Integration at 0.25 for added safety, and allocate 0.05 each to System and Agentic, with Workflow at 0.0.\n\nNow refining the final answers and test descriptions.\n\nFor references to specific points, the minimum is Agentic. A mocked LLM always returns fixed output, so it can't reveal whether the real model actually incorporates the context or falls back to generic boilerplate. Testing requires feeding actual email content with distinct details—meeting times, action items, concerns—to a real LLM and confirming the draft mentions all three by name, date, or item. This is plan-consistent since only a genuine LLM call exposes whether the model truly processes the input. Probabilities: Unit 0.05, Integration 0.1, System 0.05, Agentic 0.75, Workflow 0.05.\n\nFor contradiction detection, the minimum depends on implementation. If rule-based, Integration suffices; if LLM-based, Agentic is needed. The test populates a knowledge base with facts, generates a draft containing contradictory claims, and verifies the system flags the inconsistency.\n\nWhen the knowledge base is empty for a topic, the system should include a disclaimer and avoid fabricating unsourced facts. A real LLM might hallucinate despite instructions not to, whereas a mocked one that \"doesn't fabricate\" always passes. Testing requires an actual LLM to catch this behavior. Probabilities: Unit 0.05, Integration 0.1, System 0.05, Agentic 0.75, Workflow 0.05.\n\nFor approval workflows, the minimum level is Unit. A draft should never be sent without approval. real email thread, run full pipeline, verify: (a) draft is generated with context, (b) fact check completes, (c) draft presented to approval UI, (d) approval mechanism is present. Use real or realistic email data. This requires Workflow level testing since the complete sequence involves multiple agentic steps (draft generation, fact-checking) with real I/O across email parsing, LLM calls, knowledge base lookups, and approval flows. Integration-level tests with mocked components would miss failures at the boundaries between these systems. The probability distribution reflects this: Workflow at 0.6, Agentic at 0.15, System at 0.1, Integration at 0.1, Unit at 0.05.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13411,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13411},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1acb2fe6-9f4e-4e28-9029-709a4cbafdcd","uuid":"757c0480-b486-48fd-a586-8cb12db88e5c"}
